 #include <stdio.h>
        void main()
        {
            char *a[10] = {"hi", "hello", "how"};
            printf("%d\n", sizeof(a));
        }


///////////////////////////////////
Output: 80

This means:

a is an array of 10 pointers to char

Each element stores the address of a string.

So memory looks like:

a[0] → "hi"
a[1] → "hello"
a[2] → "how"
a[3] → NULL (or uninitialized)
...
a[9]

Important point:

Even though only 3 strings are initialized, the array still has 10 pointer elements.

2️⃣ Size of each element

Each element is a pointer to char:

char *

On most systems:

pointer size = 8 bytes (64-bit system)
pointer size = 4 bytes (32-bit system)
